                                    "data_source": "world_news_api",
                                    "abstract": "Pakistan and China have held discussions regarding the use of Afghan territory by the banned Tehreek-e-Taliban Pakistan (TTP) and its affiliates, as well as new evidence of how the neighboring country is threatening regional stability. The discussions took place during a visit by China's special envoy to Afghanistan, Ambassador Yue Xiaoyong, to Islamabad. The Chinese diplomat met with Pakistani officials to discuss the situation in Afghanistan, including the continued use of Afghan territory by terrorist groups such as the TTP. Despite repeated calls from Pakistan and the international community, the Afghan Taliban have not done enough to curb the actions of these groups. Pakistan has urged China to take a united stance against the Afghan Taliban to persuade them to keep the promises they made to the international community.",
                                    "content": "Senators ask Biden administration to back raising pilot retirement age13.5 tons of deadly gas released at Texas refinery in October incidentGreece hit by general strike as workers protest high cost of livingManufacturer to pay Philadelphia man wounded by holstered pistol\n\n Pakistan, China discuss TTP terror hubs as Afghan Taliban fail to actISLAMABAD, Pakistan - Pakistan has updated China on the usage of Afghan land by the banned Tehreek-e-Taliban Pakistan (TTP) and its affiliates, as well as new proof of how the neighboring country is jeopardizing regional stability.According to government sources, the proof was discussed with China's special envoy to Afghanistan, Ambassador Yue Xiaoyong, during his visit to Islamabad on Monday.The Chinese senior diplomat on Afghan affairs arrived in the capital just days after Russian special envoy Zamir Kabulov visited Islamabad to discuss the latest developments in the neighboring nation with Pakistani officials. According to a statement issued by the Foreign Office, the Chinese special envoy met with Foreign Secretary Amna Baloch. He also discussed this in-depth with Ambassador Ahmad Naseem Warraich, the Additional Foreign Secretary for Afghanistan and West Asia.\"The two sides discussed relations with Afghanistan. They emphasized the crucial role of neighboring nations in ensuring a peaceful and stable Afghanistan,\" according to the FO's brief statement. According to sources, Pakistan briefed the Chinese envoy on the present situation in Afghanistan, including how terrorist groups such as TTP and others continue to use the neighboring country's territory. According to sources, authorities in Islamabad provided compelling proof to the Chinese diplomat regarding terrorist sanctuaries across the border that pose a threat to Pakistan's security.The Chinese envoy was informed that, despite repeated calls from Pakistan and the international community, the Afghan Taliban were not doing enough to curtail their actions. Pakistani officials urged the Chinese envoy that it was necessary to take a united stance against the Afghan Taliban to persuade them to keep the promises they made to the international community.China has previously attempted to arbitrate between Pakistan and the Afghan Taliban administration on the issue of TTP, but earlier attempts have failed to yield results. The main reason was that the interim Taliban government refused to use force to remove TTP terrorists from its territory.Pakistan believes China still has influence over the Taliban and may pressure Kabul to address Islamabad's concerns.Since the Taliban regained control of Afghanistan in August 2021, Pakistan has seen an increase in terrorist strikes. Islamabad was initially overjoyed with the Taliban's return because it believed they would not allow Afghan soil to be used against Pakistan. However, contrary to expectations, the TTP and other terrorist groups were merely emboldened during Taliban control. The Afghan Taliban's failure to act against the TTP has harmed the bilateral relationship to the point where the two countries now retain minimal contact.Pakistan has made it clear that any development in bilateral collaboration is dependent on the Taliban taking serious and verifiable action against terrorist sanctuaries. \n\n Pakistan, China discuss TTP terror hubs as Afghan Taliban fail to actPakistan, China discuss TTP terror hubs as Afghan Taliban fail to actKhalid Umar Malik 21st November 2024, 07:25 GMT+11ISLAMABAD, Pakistan - Pakistan has updated China on the usage of Afghan land by the banned Tehreek-e-Taliban Pakistan (TTP) and its affiliates, as well as new proof of how the neighboring country is jeopardizing regional stability.According to government sources, the proof was discussed with China's special envoy to Afghanistan, Ambassador Yue Xiaoyong, during his visit to Islamabad on Monday.The Chinese senior diplomat on Afghan affairs arrived in the capital just days after Russian special envoy Zamir Kabulov visited Islamabad to discuss the latest developments in the neighboring nation with Pakistani officials. According to a statement issued by the Foreign Office, the Chinese special envoy met with Foreign Secretary Amna Baloch. He also discussed this in-depth with Ambassador Ahmad Naseem Warraich, the Additional Foreign Secretary for Afghanistan and West Asia.\"The two sides discussed relations with Afghanistan. They emphasized the crucial role of neighboring nations in ensuring a peaceful and stable Afghanistan,\" according to the FO's brief statement. According to sources, Pakistan briefed the Chinese envoy on the present situation in Afghanistan, including how terrorist groups such as TTP and others continue to use the neighboring country's territory. According to sources, authorities in Islamabad provided compelling proof to the Chinese diplomat regarding terrorist sanctuaries across the border that pose a threat to Pakistan's security.The Chinese envoy was informed that, despite repeated calls from Pakistan and the international community, the Afghan Taliban were not doing enough to curtail their actions. Pakistani officials urged the Chinese envoy that it was necessary to take a united stance against the Afghan Taliban to persuade them to keep the promises they made to the international community.China has previously attempted to arbitrate between Pakistan and the Afghan Taliban administration on the issue of TTP, but earlier attempts have failed to yield results. The main reason was that the interim Taliban government refused to use force to remove TTP terrorists from its territory.Pakistan believes China still has influence over the Taliban and may pressure Kabul to address Islamabad's concerns.Since the Taliban regained control of Afghanistan in August 2021, Pakistan has seen an increase in terrorist strikes. Islamabad was initially overjoyed with the Taliban's return because it believed they would not allow Afghan soil to be used against Pakistan. However, contrary to expectations, the TTP and other terrorist groups were merely emboldened during Taliban control. The Afghan Taliban's failure to act against the TTP has harmed the bilateral relationship to the point where the two countries now retain minimal contact.Pakistan has made it clear that any development in bilateral collaboration is dependent on the Taliban taking serious and verifiable action against terrorist sanctuaries. \n\n Read This Next US Creek Indians to purchase racecourse in AlabamaFord faces weak EV sales, to cut 4,000 jobs in Europe, UKScottish farm selling UK's most expensive cup of coffee at $344Comcast to spin off cable networks MSNBC and CNBCTarget struggles in third quarter despite price cuts \n\nBig News Network ASSOCIATESBig News Network News AgencyMidwest Radio NetworkMainstream Media BIG NEWS NETWORK.COM About us Contact & SupportTerms & ConditionsSitemap PRODUCTS & SERVICES News Releases NewsletterArchive FOLLOW US Facebook Twitter Google+ RSS Feeds Copyright © 1998-2024 Big News Network All rights reserved. ISSN: 2616-6917",
